 as accurate as melee combat. At most you should be off by about 1-3 percent of the pet's health(due to the regeneration that takes place while you are castin and what you mentioned). <br>
<br>
In the case of the epic pet, 1 percent is roughly 40 HP as a ballpart figure. Soo 120 HP variable. <br>
<br>
Furthermore, melee combat does have a margin of error as well. such as if the pet is hit for 160 damage, while having only 60 HP left. In such an instance, the margin of error would be 100 HP. This margin of error would actually increase with pets with a smaller amount of HP. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/urekcim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rekcim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#333333>(8/16/02 8:28:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=640.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pet Hit Points - GVoc: Earth, Air, Water // MSIII /// Ep</span><hr size=1> Wow, your epic has more hps then an unbuffed 60 warrior.  Buff that pet up with Aego and focus=SWEET. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uiblisthemage.showPublicProfile?language=EN>IblisTheMage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 67<br> <font color=#333333>(8/17/02 7:19:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=640.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pet Hit Points - GVoc: Earth, Air, Water // MSIII /// Ep</span><hr size=1> Great work! <br>
